        <div id="resultsMoreBlock" class="results-more-block" style="display:none">
          <button type="button" class="more-files-btn" id="moreFilesBtn">
            <span id="moreFilesLabel"></span>
          </button>
          <div id="resultsMore" class="results results-more-inner" hidden></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="actions" id="actions" style="display:none">
        <button class="btn btn-lg" id="downloadAll">⬇ Download All as ZIP</button>
        <button class="btn btn-secondary btn-lg" id="clearAll">Clear All</button>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Educational content (SEO) -->
  <article class="heic-edu" aria-label="Guide: HEIC format and converting to JPG">
    <div class="container heic-edu-inner">
      <section class="heic-edu-block">
        <h2 id="what-is-heic">What is HEIC (and why your iPhone uses it)?</h2>
        <p>
          If you have ever asked <strong>what is HEIC</strong> after opening your camera roll on a PC, you are not alone. <strong>HEIC</strong> stands for <em>High Efficiency Image Container</em> — a modern container format that Apple adopted broadly starting with <strong>iOS 11 in 2017</strong>. Today, most <strong>iPhone HEIC photos</strong> are saved in this format by default because it pairs very efficient compression with rich image data in a single <strong>HEIC file</strong>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Under the hood, HEIC typically stores images compressed with <strong>HEVC (H.265)</strong>, which can produce files that are often <strong>around 50% smaller than JPG</strong> at similar visual quality. That matters on devices with finite storage and for iCloud backups. The <strong>HEIC format</strong> also supports features many JPEG workflows skip: <strong>Live Photos</strong> (still plus motion), <strong>depth information</strong> for Portrait mode, and <strong>HDR</strong> and wide color when your capture pipeline provides them.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Why did Apple choose HEIC?</strong> In one word: <strong>storage efficiency</strong> — smaller files with excellent quality, which keeps your phone fast and your library manageable. The same logic applies across the ecosystem: <strong>HEIC is used on iPad</strong> and is common on <strong>macOS</strong> when capturing or exporting photos in Apple’s default workflows. The trade-off is compatibility: outside Apple’s world, many apps, sites, and older systems still expect a plain <strong>JPG</strong> — which is why learning to <strong>convert HEIC to JPG</strong> remains essential for sharing and archiving.
        </p>
        <p>
          HEIC is part of the broader HEIF family standardized for modern imaging; you will still hear people say “HEIF” when they mean the same kind of file. Whether you call it <strong>HEIC format</strong> or HEIF, the practical takeaway is the same: great on Apple devices, often awkward everywhere else without a deliberate <strong>HEIC file</strong> conversion step.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="heic-edu-block">
        <h2 id="why-convert">Why you need to convert HEIC to JPG</h2>
        <p>
          You do not convert because HEIC is “bad” — you convert because the rest of the world has not fully caught up. When you need to <strong>share iPhone photos</strong> with someone on Windows who has not installed codecs or extensions, a <strong>JPG</strong> attachment opens everywhere. The same friction appears when you <strong>convert HEIC to JPG</strong> for the web: many upload forms, job portals, and older CMS backends quietly reject unfamiliar extensions even when the image is fine.
        </p>
        <p>
          Think about the last time you emailed vacation pictures to a relative on Android, or tried to upload a headshot to an application that only accepted JPEG. Those are everyday <strong>HEIC compatibility</strong> problems. Printing at many retail labs and kiosk workflows still assumes <strong>iphone photos to JPG</strong> — not raw iPhone captures — and forums or legacy intranet tools often choke on anything but common formats.
        </p>
        <p>
          Creators and professionals hit the same wall: older desktop editors (for example, Photoshop builds from before broad HEIC support) and many free tools expect raster interchange in JPEG. Embedding images in <strong>Word</strong> or <strong>Google Docs</strong>, dropping files into slide decks, or filing long-term archives in a format you can open in ten years all point to the same conclusion: <strong>JPG</strong> is the universal lingua franca. Converting bridges Apple’s efficient capture format with workflows that still standardize on JPEG — without forcing anyone else to install special software.
        </p>
        <p>
          Even when you are not “technical,” you feel <strong>heic compatibility</strong> as friction: a download that will not open, an upload spinner that never finishes, or a colleague asking you to “resend as JPEG.” Fixing that once — by batch-converting before you send — saves repeated confusion and keeps focus on the photo, not the file type.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="heic-edu-block">
        <h2 id="how-to-convert">How to convert HEIC to JPG in your browser</h2>
        <p>
          This page uses standard browser capabilities together with client-side decoding so you can convert without uploading your library to a server. The heavy lifting — reading each <strong>HEIC file</strong>, turning it into pixels, and re-encoding as JPEG — happens through JavaScript APIs in your tab, similar to how offline-capable web apps preview images before export. Follow these steps:
        </p>
        <ol class="heic-steps">
          <li>
            <strong>Add your files.</strong> Drop <strong>HEIC</strong> files onto the converter, or click the dropzone to browse. You can convert a single <strong>HEIC file</strong> or a <strong>batch</strong> at once. Drag-and-drop works from <strong>Finder</strong> on Mac or <strong>File Explorer</strong> on Windows.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Decode locally.</strong> Files are decoded in your browser using JavaScript — there is <strong>no upload to any server</strong>; your photos stay on your device. The tool relies on the same kind of client-side processing modern web apps use for previews and exports.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Check quality.</strong> Review the converted <strong>JPG</strong> output. The default is <strong>100% quality</strong> for the best match to your original still. Open <strong>Advanced options</strong> if you need smaller downloads (balanced or smaller file presets).
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Download.</strong> Save each file with its download button, or use <strong>Download All as ZIP</strong> when you converted many images — ideal for batches from an event or a folder export.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Privacy after you leave.</strong> When you close the tab, converted data held in memory is cleared automatically — nothing is stored in the cloud by this tool, and there are no accounts tying conversions to you.
          </li>
        </ol>
      </section>

      <section class="heic-edu-block">
        <h2 id="heic-vs-jpg">HEIC vs JPG: Key differences</h2>
        <div class="heic-table-wrap">
          <table class="heic-compare-table">
            <caption class="sr-only">Comparison of HEIC and JPG features</caption>
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th scope="col">Feature</th>
                <th scope="col">HEIC</th>
                <th scope="col">JPG</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td>Year introduced</td><td>2015 (Apple 2017)</td><td>1992</td></tr>
              <tr><td>File size</td><td>~50% smaller</td><td>Baseline</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Quality at same size</td><td>Better</td><td>Good</td></tr>
              <tr><td>iPhone support</td><td>Native</td><td>Native</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Windows support</td><td>Limited (extension needed)</td><td>Native</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Android support</td><td>Limited (newer versions only)</td><td>Native</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Web browsers</td><td>Not widely supported</td><td>Universal</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Editing software</td><td>Newer apps only</td><td>Universal</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Transparency</td><td>Yes</td><td>No</td></tr>
              <tr><td>Animation</td><td>Yes</td><td>No</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p>
          Use <strong>HEIC</strong> when you want maximum efficiency and advanced capture features on Apple devices; use <strong>JPG</strong> when you need maximum compatibility — email, the open web, print shops, and mixed-device groups. <a href="/blog/heic-vs-jpg">Read our detailed HEIC vs JPG comparison for the full analysis.</a>
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="heic-edu-block">
        <h2 id="who-converts">Who typically converts HEIC files?</h2>
        <ul class="heic-audience-list">
          <li>
            <strong>iPhone users sharing with Windows or Android family.</strong> When relatives cannot open attachments, <strong>iphone to windows photos</strong> workflows are smoother with <strong>JPG</strong> — no codec hunt required.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Professionals emailing clients on older systems.</strong> A single universal attachment reduces back-and-forth and protects <strong>HEIC compatibility</strong> headaches on the receiving end.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Job seekers uploading profile photos.</strong> Many portals only accept JPEG; converting first avoids silent upload failures.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Real estate photographers delivering to MLS systems.</strong> Listing backends often standardize on JPEG for consistency and speed.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Content creators posting to picky platforms.</strong> If the uploader rejects your file, <strong>share iPhone photos</strong> as <strong>JPG</strong> and move on.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Photographers archiving for the long term.</strong> A universally readable format complements camera originals.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Students submitting assignment photos.</strong> School portals and LMS tools frequently cap formats to JPEG or PNG.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Travelers sharing trip albums with mixed-device groups.</strong> One format keeps the group chat or shared folder drama-free.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          In each case, the goal is predictable delivery: when you <strong>share iPhone photos</strong> as <strong>JPG</strong>, recipients do not need to know what <strong>HEIC</strong> is — they only need to open the attachment or upload field and move on.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="heic-edu-block">
        <h2 id="troubleshooting">Common HEIC conversion issues and solutions</h2>
        <p>
          Most conversions complete in seconds, but a few edge cases are worth knowing. <strong>Very large HEIC files (over about 50MB)</strong> can make your browser work harder — close heavy tabs or pause other apps so memory stays available. <strong>Live Photos</strong> contain motion plus a still; tools like this one convert the <strong>still image</strong> to <strong>JPG</strong>, while the motion portion is not carried over. Similarly, <strong>Portrait mode depth data</strong> does not survive in a flat JPEG because standard JPG does not embed that channel the same way.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Older browsers</strong> may lack reliable HEIC decode paths; use a current version of Chrome, Edge, Firefox, or Safari. If a file has unusual metadata or corruption, try opening it in Photos and exporting again, or re-save from the source app before converting. That single step resolves many odd one-off failures.
        </p>
        <p>
          If conversion feels slow only on one machine, compare against another browser or device: extensions, aggressive privacy blockers, or low memory can all make the same <strong>HEIC</strong> feel “stuck” even when the file itself is healthy. Retry after a refresh with fewer tabs open for the most reliable experience.
        </p>
      </section>
    </div>
  </article>

  <!-- FAQ -->
  <section class="faq">
    <div class="container">
      <h2 class="section-title">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <div class="faq-item"><h4>Is this really free and unlimited?</h4><p>Yes. No limits, no signup, no watermarks. The site runs entirely in your browser.</p></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><h4>Are my files safe?</h4><p>Absolutely. Files never leave your device. We can't see, store, or access them.</p></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><h4>What is HEIC and why convert it?</h4><p>HEIC is Apple's iPhone image format. It's not supported on Windows, Android, or many websites — converting to JPG ensures compatibility everywhere.</p></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><h4>Will I lose quality?</h4><p>Default is maximum (100%) JPEG quality. Use Advanced options to pick Balanced or Small file if you want a smaller download.</p></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><h4>Does it work on mobile?</h4><p>Yes — works on iPhone, iPad, Android, and any modern browser.</p></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><h4>What's the maximum file size?</h4><p>There's no imposed limit — it's bound by your device's RAM. Typical iPhone photos (2-5MB HEIC) convert instantly. Very large files (50MB+) may take a few seconds.</p></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><h4>Does converting lose quality?</h4><p>At default 100% quality, visual difference is imperceptible. JPG files will be 2-3× larger than the original HEIC since JPG uses less efficient compression.</p></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><h4>Can I batch convert a whole folder?</h4><p>Yes — select multiple files at once or drag an entire folder onto the dropzone. Download all converted files as a single ZIP.</p></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><h4>Does this work on iPhone and iPad?</h4><p>Yes — opens in Safari, Chrome, or Firefox on iOS. You can select HEIC photos directly from your Photos library.</p></div>
        <div class="faq-item"><h4>Is there a monthly conversion limit?</h4><p>No. Convert as many files as you want, as often as you want. There are no accounts, no quotas, and no premium tiers.</p></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="heic-related" aria-label="Related tools and guides">
    <div class="container">
      <h2 class="section-title">Related tools</h2>
      <ul class="heic-related-grid">
        <li><a href="/image/webp-to-jpg">WebP to JPG Converter</a></li>
        <li><a href="/image/image-compressor">Image Compressor</a></li>
        <li><a href="/image/avif-to-jpg">AVIF to JPG Converter</a></li>
        <li><a href="/image/image-resizer">Image Resizer</a></li>
      </ul>
      <h2 class="section-title section-title-sub">Related guides</h2>
      <ul class="heic-related-grid heic-related-guides">
        <li><a href="/blog/open-heic-windows-11">How to Open HEIC Files on Windows 11</a></li>
        <li><a href="/blog/heic-vs-jpg">HEIC vs JPG: Complete Comparison</a></li>
        <li><a href="/blog/convert-iphone-photos-to-jpg">Convert iPhone Photos to JPG</a></li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <script is:inline>
    document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
      const dropzone = document.getElementById('dropzone');
      const fileInput = document.getElementById('fileInput');
      const results = document.getElementById('results');
      const actions = document.getElementById('actions');
      const banner = document.getElementById('successBanner');
      const bannerText = document.getElementById('bannerText');
      const resultsHeader = document.getElementById('resultsHeader');
      const fileCount = document.getElementById('fileCount');
      const resultsMore = document.getElementById('resultsMore');
      let converted = [];

      function formatSizeForCompare(bytes) {
        const mb = bytes / (1024 * 1024);
        if (mb >= 0.01) return mb.toFixed(2) + ' MB';
        return (bytes / 1024).toFixed(1) + ' KB';
      }

      function getJpegQuality() {
        const btn = document.querySelector('.preset-btn.is-selected');
        return btn ? parseInt(btn.dataset.q, 10) / 100 : 1;
      }

      function wireQualityPresets() {
        const hintMain = document.getElementById('hintMain');
        const presetDesc = document.getElementById('presetDesc');
        const toggleAdvanced = document.getElementById('toggleAdvanced');
        const advancedPanel = document.getElementById('advancedPanel');
        const HINT = {
          '100': 'Converting at maximum quality',
          '85': 'Converting at balanced quality (85%)',
          '70': 'Converting for smallest file size (70%)',
        };
        const DESC = {
          '100': '100% quality — best fidelity, largest JPEGs.',
          '85': '85% — smaller files with minimal visible loss.',
          '70': '70% — smallest files; more compression visible.',
        };

        function syncPresetLabels() {
          const sel = document.querySelector('.preset-btn.is-selected');
          const q = sel ? sel.dataset.q : '100';
          if (hintMain) hintMain.textContent = HINT[q] || HINT['100'];
          if (presetDesc) presetDesc.textContent = DESC[q] || DESC['100'];
        }

        document.querySelectorAll('.preset-btn').forEach((btn) => {
          btn.addEventListener('click', () => {
            document.querySelectorAll('.preset-btn').forEach((b) => {
              b.classList.remove('is-selected');
              b.setAttribute('aria-checked', 'false');
            });
            btn.classList.add('is-selected');
            btn.setAttribute('aria-checked', 'true');
            syncPresetLabels();
          });
        });

        toggleAdvanced?.addEventListener('click', () => {
          const open = advancedPanel.hidden;
          advancedPanel.hidden = !open;
          toggleAdvanced.setAttribute('aria-expanded', open ? 'true' : 'false');
        });

        syncPresetLabels();
      }

      wireQualityPresets();

      dropzone.addEventListener('click', () => fileInput.click());
      dropzone.addEventListener('dragover', e => { e.preventDefault(); dropzone.classList.add('drag'); });
      dropzone.addEventListener('dragleave', () => dropzone.classList.remove('drag'));
      dropzone.addEventListener('drop', e => {
        e.preventDefault();
        dropzone.classList.remove('drag');
        handleFiles(Array.from(e.dataTransfer.files));
      });
      fileInput.addEventListener('change', e => {
        const fs = Array.from(e.target.files);
        e.target.value = '';
        handleFiles(fs);
      });

      async function handleFiles(files) {
        if (typeof heic2any === 'undefined') {
          alert('Library not loaded. Please refresh.');
          return;
        }
        if (!files || !files.length) return;

        const total = files.length;
        results.innerHTML = '';
        if (resultsMore) resultsMore.innerHTML = '';
        const moreBlock = document.getElementById('resultsMoreBlock');
        if (moreBlock) moreBlock.style.display = 'none';
        const toolbar = document.getElementById('resultsToolbar');
        if (toolbar) toolbar.style.display = 'none';
        const note = document.getElementById('galleryToolbarNote');
        if (note) note.hidden = true;

        banner.style.display = 'block';
        banner.className = 'banner banner-info';
        bannerText.textContent = '⏳ Converting ' + total + ' file(s)...';

        const quality = getJpegQuality();
        let idx = 0;

        for (const file of files) {
          const parent = window.DoItSwiftFileResults
            ? DoItSwiftFileResults.getAppendParent(results, resultsMore, idx)
            : results;
          idx += 1;

          const item = document.createElement('div');
          item.className = 'file-item';
          item.innerHTML = `
            <div class="file-item-main">
              <div class="file-thumb" aria-hidden="true">🖼️</div>
              <div class="file-info">
                <div class="file-name"></div>
                <div class="file-status">Converting…</div>
                <div class="progress-bar"><div class="progress-fill"></div></div>
              </div>
              <div class="file-actions-col">
                <button type="button" class="btn-text btn-preview" disabled style="visibility:hidden">Preview</button>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="file-preview-panel" hidden>
              <img alt="Preview" />
            </div>
          `;
          item.querySelector('.file-name').textContent = file.name;
          parent.appendChild(item);
          const fill = item.querySelector('.progress-fill');
          const status = item.querySelector('.file-status');
          fill.style.width = '40%';

          try {
            const blob = await heic2any({ blob: file, toType: 'image/jpeg', quality });
            const finalBlob = Array.isArray(blob) ? blob[0] : blob;
            const url = URL.createObjectURL(finalBlob);
            const newName = file.name.replace(/\.(heic|heif)$/i, '.jpg');
            converted.push({ name: newName, blob: finalBlob });
            fill.style.width = '100%';
            status.className = 'file-status done';
            status.innerHTML =
              '<span class="size-compare">Original: ' +
              formatSizeForCompare(file.size) +
              ' → Converted: ' +
              formatSizeForCompare(finalBlob.size) +
              '</span>';
            const actionsCol = item.querySelector('.file-actions-col');
            const dl = document.createElement('a');
            dl.href = url;
            dl.download = newName;
            dl.className = 'btn';
            dl.textContent = 'Download';
            actionsCol.appendChild(dl);
            if (window.DoItSwiftFileResults) {
              DoItSwiftFileResults.initCompletedRow(item, url);
            }
          } catch (err) {
            fill.style.width = '100%';
            fill.style.background = '#ef4444';
            status.className = 'file-status error';
            status.textContent = 'Error: ' + (err.message || 'Failed');
          }
        }

        if (converted.length) {
          actions.style.display = 'flex';
          resultsHeader.style.display = 'block';
          fileCount.textContent = converted.length;
          banner.className = 'banner banner-success';
          bannerText.textContent = '✓ ' + converted.length + ' file(s) ready — see list below';
          banner.scrollIntoView({ behavior: 'smooth', block: 'center' });
          const batchOver10 = total > 10;
          if (window.DoItSwiftFileResults) {
            DoItSwiftFileResults.setupToolbar({
              toolbar: document.getElementById('resultsToolbar'),
              galleryToggle: document.getElementById('galleryViewToggle'),
              note: document.getElementById('galleryToolbarNote'),
              batchOver10,
              galleryRoot: document.getElementById('fileResultsRoot'),
            });
            if (total > 10) {
              DoItSwiftFileResults.setupMoreFilesSection({
                moreBlock: document.getElementById('resultsMoreBlock'),
                moreInner: document.getElementById('resultsMore'),
                moreBtn: document.getElementById('moreFilesBtn'),
                moreLabel: document.getElementById('moreFilesLabel'),
                extraCount: total - 10,
              });
            }
          }
        }
      }

      document.getElementById('clearAll').addEventListener('click', () => {
        results.innerHTML = '';
        if (resultsMore) resultsMore.innerHTML = '';
        const moreBlock = document.getElementById('resultsMoreBlock');
        if (moreBlock) moreBlock.style.display = 'none';
        const tb = document.getElementById('resultsToolbar');
        if (tb) tb.style.display = 'none';
        const gt = document.getElementById('galleryViewToggle');
        if (gt) {
          gt.checked = false;
          gt.disabled = false;
        }
        const note = document.getElementById('galleryToolbarNote');
        if (note) note.hidden = true;
        converted = [];
        actions.style.display = 'none';
        banner.style.display = 'none';
        resultsHeader.style.display = 'none';
      });

      document.getElementById('downloadAll').addEventListener('click', async () => {
        if (typeof JSZip === 'undefined') return alert('ZIP library not loaded.');
        const zip = new JSZip();
        converted.forEach(f => zip.file(f.name, f.blob));
        const content = await zip.generateAsync({ type: 'blob' });
        const url = URL.createObjectURL(content);
        const a = document.createElement('a');
        a.href = url;
        a.download = 'doitswift-converted.zip';
        a.click();
      });

      void (async () => {
        try {
          const pending = await window.DoItSwiftPending?.consume?.();
          if (pending) await handleFiles([pending]);
        } catch (e) {
          console.warn(e);
        }
      })();
    });
  </script>

